<HEADLINE>
<P>
ERMA BOMBECK: COUNT YOUR BLESSINGS ON THANKSGIVING DAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ERMA BOMBECK 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's the best of all holidays. You don't have to wear a costume. You don't have 
to buy a present or trim a tree. You don't have to hide eggs, buy a new outfit, 
be a valentine or shoot off fireworks. 
</P>
<P>
Thanksgiving is a day we celebrate family. Kids watch the parades, men watch 
football and women watch turkeys brown. It has always been that way. 
</P>
<P>
As a kid, I remember it as a day my grandfather was allowed to smoke cigars in 
the house. A day when all the children were allowed to bang on the piano 
without Grandma closing the lid on their fingers. A day when no one ragged my 
Uncle Wesley about getting a job or reminded my Aunt Mildred she didn't need 
another baby. 
</P>
<P>
It was a day Grandma baked extra loaves of yeast bread for everyone to take 
home, and no one complained about the cost of the food we were eating. It was a 
day that, no matter how poor we were, nickels and dimes always appeared to send 
the kids to the neighborhood picture show after dinner. 
</P>
<P>
I can never remember my family offering grace or thanks before a Thanksgiving 
dinner. They seemed to want to, but they felt like they didn't have the right 
words. So my uncle would yell something like "Over the lips and over the gums, 
watch out stomach, here it comes." 
</P>
<P>
Given that, there was something significant about our reunions: We all showed 
up for them. I cannot remember a Thanksgiving that all of Grandma's children 
and their large families were not seated on milk boxes, piano stools, vanity 
benches, folding chairs and glider swings around her table. 
</P>
<P>
And in return for our dedication, we took something away with us: a sense of 
belonging to something that was bigger than us, richer than us, better than us, 
stronger than us -- that would outlive us all. If there was a death, 
unemployment, ill health, domestic problems, it didn't matter. Every 
Thanksgiving, we all returned to that house to bind up our wounds before we 
returned again to life outside the cocoon. But we always knew it was there. 
</P>
<P>
It doesn't matter if the dishes don't match, there aren't enough chairs to go 
around, you're using soup spoons to stir coffee, the turkey is too small, the 
pumpkin pies are runny, you borrowed from the credit union to get there, and 
all the kids are driving you crazy. 
</P>
<P>
You have a place to be, and you are blessed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
