<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY DIGEST: LYNWOOD; 
</P>
<P>
SCHOOL GETS COMPUTER LAB TO TEACH READING, WRITING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A $25,000 computer lab to teach kindergarten and first-grade pupils reading and 
writing has been installed at Mark Twain Elementary School in the Lynwood 
Unified School District. 
</P>
<P>
The computer-assisted program, called "Writing to Read," uses IBM computers and 
was made available through the Riordan Foundation of Los Angeles and City Bank 
of Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
The bank provided the funds for the lab and the Riordan Foundation trained the 
teachers. 
</P>
<P>
The lab, which has 12 computers and will serve more than 200 during the school 
year, officially opened last week. 
</P>
<P>
The foundation has contributed millions of dollars to inner-city schools 
throughout the nation for computer programs to teach elementary pupils reading 
and writing. 
</P>
<P>
It has contributed more than $150,000 in computer equipment to the Lynwood 
school district during the last two years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA112290-0123 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 311782 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 22, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Long Beach; Part J; Page 2; Column 3 
</P>
</SECTION>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, They've All Earned an A-Plus: Sixteen teachers from the Southeast/Long 
Beach area were among 74 honored by the Los Angeles County Office of Education 
recently during a luncheon at the Sheraton Cerritos hotel. All of them are 
teachers of the year in their respective districts for the 1990-91 school year. 
Some of the honorees, from left, Marilyn G. McQuown, West Covina Unified School 
District; Anne Taylor, Bursch Elementary School, Compton Unified School 
District; Lois A. Kock, Redondo Beach City School District; Glen C. Kaskela, 
Paramount High School, Paramount Unified School District; Nancy A. Gaines, 
Mayfair High School, Bellflower Unified School District; Diane Beeman, Warren 
High School, Downey Unified School District. ; Photo, Other teacher honorees 
from the Long Beach Unified School District are, from left, Miriam Hernandez 
Garcia, Roosevelt Elementary School; Michael A. Smith, Wilson High School; and 
Geri Johnson, Newcomb Elementary School. Last year's county teacher of the 
year, Norma Mota-Altman of Alhambra, spoke to the group. Frank J. Alderete, 
president of the Los Angeles County Board of Education, and Stuart E. Gothold, 
county superintendent of schools, also addressed the group. SARAH M. BROWN / 
For The Times 
</P>
