<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY DIGESTERS: CHEERS FOR THE HOME TEAM 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Perennial powerhouse Wilson High School of Hacienda Heights pulled out a narrow 
victory in the Super Quiz of the ninth Los Angeles County Academic Decathlon 
held Saturday at Gahr High School in Cerritos. 
</P>
<P>
Wilson's last contestant was senior Michelle Ivey, whose father teaches math at 
La Serna High School in Whittier. 
</P>
<P>
Ivey answered all five of her questions correctly on the topic of astronauts 
and space travel to ice her team's narrow win over West High School of 
Torrance. 
</P>
<P>
The Super Quiz, which resembles a raucous game show, is the only public segment 
of the decathlon, which tests students in 10 subject areas, including science, 
social studies, writing, public speaking and fine arts. 
</P>
<P>
The team that places first in the overall competition will represent Los 
Angeles County in the state competition. The victor will be announced next 
Wednesday at a banquet in Montebello. 
</P>
<P>
But all the teams are winners, said Compton teacher and team coach Nancy 
Miller. "We're getting all this positive attention for academics, and it rubs 
off on other students," she said. 
</P>
<P>
Contestant Ramiro Medina of Compton said he could barely speak English six 
years ago. Now he is getting straight As and competing for his school. "The 
decathlon is important not just because we want to win, but for the experience. 
It's helped me to become a well-rounded person," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Bleachers full of students from Compton erupt with cheers when their 
team scores well in Academic Decathlon competition. ROBERT GABRIEL / Los 
Angeles Times 
</P>
