<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: COUNCIL DELAYS VOTE ON BRUSH REMOVAL LAW 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Glendale City Council on Tuesday delayed a final vote on a sweeping brush 
fire prevention ordinance that would require firefighters to check 13,000 
hillside lots for vegetation that could fuel a fast-moving blaze. 
</P>
<P>
Adoption of the measure, which received preliminary approval last week, was 
postponed after homeowner associations complained that it did not give property 
owners enough time to comply with an order to remove brush. 
</P>
<P>
As proposed, firefighters could order a property owner to clear hazardous brush 
within 15 days. If not done, the city could send crews to clear the brush 10 
days later and bill the owner for the removal costs. 
</P>
<P>
City staff members agreed to review the notification guidelines and return the 
measure to the council Dec. 4. 
</P>
</TEXT>
